This case is being appealed. If the court makes a decision in a case that a party disagrees with, the party may have the right to seek review by a higher court to determine if the trial court's decision was correct. Appeals are most often made after a trial or final decision in a case, but an appeal can also occur before a final decision.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

01:34 PM Defendant Tommy M Canady in court with attorney Jefren Olsen.  Defendant Tommy M Canady in custody.  Rebecca L Sommers appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court Reporter Leslie Johnson.
The Court has received correspondence from the State agreeing that today should be used as a hearing to return the defendant's property and that the Machner hearing be rescheduled and that a new schedule for briefing the Machner issues be determined. The State has no reason to believe that this laptop belongs to anyone but the defendant nor has anyone else claimed ownership. The State has a forensic copy and does not object to the laptop being returned.
Defense asks that a forensic copy of the laptop be shared with them as well as it would be easier for their expert. The State concedes the property return, she does not concede the O'Brien issue and because she was not aware that the issue would be brought up, she is not prepared to make an full argument. Defense expert indicates a March return date is very doable for him to be able to examine the laptop.

BTC: Laptop may be returned to defense counsel; defense will e-file the order for the Courts signature. State's response brief and arguments are due 3/6.
